 This study attempts to address these questions by providing (in section ) 

recommendations for the data depositor, specifically about what documents
                     should accompany a resource to be archived ; 

recommendations for the archiving services, specifically about what tools
                     may be used to validate TEI XML documents ;

A teiHeader element must be provided for each distinct TEI or teiCorpus element in a resource. We recommend the following steps as part of the accession process:
Each header should be validated against a strict schema (to be supplied) which will check the existence of required components listed below;
Each header will be modified, as a minimum to indicate that the header has been validated for accession, and possibly also to indicate any significant gaps found, as indicated below.

TEI-XML resources may be derived from many different kinds of object. A sourceDescription is required for each distinct source. Depending on its nature, this will contain one of the following :
bibl or biblStruct for books, newspapers, pamphlets etc. originally printed;
msDesc for unique manuscript archival documents or inscriptions;
p or note for unpublished born-digital materials;
bibl or ref for web pages or other digitally distributed materials
recording for recorded or broadcast speech or video

The second major subdivision of the TEI header is contained by an optional encodingDesc element, and may potentially contain a very large number of semi-structured metadata elements covering most aspects of the process by which a source has been encoded. Its function thus overlaps with that of the ODD file discussed in section . Components of this element specify the methods and editorial principles which governed the transcription or encoding of the resource and may also include sets of coded definitions used by other components. The following elements, many of which have quite extensive substructure, are potentially available:
Project goals and research agenda (projectDesc);
Sampling principles and methods employed (samplingDecl);
Editorial principles and practices (editorialDecl);
XML tagging used (tagsDecl, styleDefDecl, schemaSpec);
Reference schemes applied (refsDecl ; geoDecl)
Classification scheme used (classDecl)

Note that the schemaSpec discussed in section may also appear within the encodingDesc of a particular document. We do not however recommend this for the following reasons:
full documentation of a schema requires more than simply a schema specification;
an ODD usually applies to more than one TEI document;
if a document has both an associated ODD and a schemaSpec in its header it is not clear which takes precedence in the case of disagreement between them. . If therefore a schemaSpec is present, it will only be used to validate the document in the case where no other ODD is available.

The idea of TEI Conformance goes beyond simple syntactic validity, i.e. conformance to the rules of XML. The TEI Guidelines now define quite explicitly the properties of a TEI-conformant document, and suggest ways in which those properties may be checked. They state that :
a TEI conformant document must be valid with respect to a schema called TEI All (at least, as far as those parts of it which are taken from the TEI namespace are concerned);
a TEI conformant document must be accompanied by an ODD documenting its specific TEI usage;
a TEI document must respect the TEI conceptual model: that is, it must respect the semantics of the TEI elements it contains. Clearly this constraint is hard or impossible to validate entirely automatically, though some indicative procedures can be identified.

A schema specification may express the components which are to be combined to form a
               schema in any of the following ways : 

a list of TEI modules to be included by reference; 

a list of TEI elements to be included by reference;

a subset of declarations from a named module, defined either by inclusion
                     ("select only x y and z from module a") or by exclusion ("select everything
                     except x y and z from module a") 

modifications of certain parts of an existing specification, for example to
                     change class memberships, add a new usage example, suppress one or more
                     attributes, change lists of legal attribute values, etc.

If the recommendations made in the present report are accepted, it is clear that work is needed on several fronts:
a tool kit to carry out the procedures outlined in section needs to be assembled, and tested against a substantial body of TEI documents;
cost-effective ways of enhancing and correcting existing TEI documents to meet the proposed level of description need to be determined;
the potential user community needs better guidance on how to document their resources. For example, better documentation of the ODD system is needed: a simple user guide or antisèche How To Write an ODD would be very useful.
